section.para:
The annotator requires no other layer, so it can sit anywhere in a DocumentAnalyzer. The example below builds a three-entry glossary, runs it after a model-free tokenizer, and reads GlossaryAnnotator.GLOSSARY back with exact spans. Case folding is on, so a registered lowercase term still covers a mixed-case mention while the span points at the original characters. GlossaryUsageExampleTest asserts the behavior shown here.
List<GlossaryEntry> glossary = List.of( new GlossaryEntry("LIB-1", "Apache OpenNLP"), new GlossaryEntry("ALG-42", "maximum entropy model"), new GlossaryEntry("ALG-7", "perceptron model"));
DocumentAnalyzer analyzer = DocumentAnalyzer.builder() .add(new TokenizerAnnotator(WhitespaceTokenizer.INSTANCE)) .add(new GlossaryAnnotator(new AhoCorasickGlossaryMatcher(glossary, true))) .build();
Document document = analyzer.analyze( "Apache OpenNLP ships a Maximum Entropy model and a perceptron model.");
List<Annotation<GlossaryMatch>> hits = document.get(GlossaryAnnotator.GLOSSARY); // three hits: "Apache OpenNLP", "Maximum Entropy model", "perceptron model"
A document that never saw a glossary annotator reads an empty glossary layer, and the key is absent from layers().
